HEADWORD: Dbris
<hw>D⟦eacute⟧`bris"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr.
pref. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧-</ets> (L. <ets>dis</ets>) + <ets>briser</ets> to
break, shatter; perh. of Celtic origin.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Broken and detached fragments, taken
collectively; especially, fragments detached from a rock or mountain,
and piled up at the base.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Rubbish, especially such as results from the
destruction of anything; remains; ruins.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Debruised</ent>⟦br⟧
